description.text:
This case is designed for the SainSmart LCD Smart Controller 12864, which adds an SD card slot and rotary control along with stop and backlight buttons to many 3D printer models. I had printed another design, but found that it was a bit lacking and so I felt like it was time to make my own.

This design is screwless, and the display assembly should sit on the rear posts with the top clamping on afterward, with no issues even at a low print quality. I did not leave any openings for the contrast and backlight adjustment pots, so you should be sure to adjust those before installation.Two buttons are on the front of the display, marked with S for stop and L for light, and they should be able to flex enough to hit the buttons on the control PCB.

This first version does not include a knob for the adjustment dial, but I may add one in later revisions. I will also be uploading my original files once I've cleaned up the grouping and component names.

As the case isn't built for any particular mounting or fastener, I'll probably be adding an angled stand to it soon, at which point I will update this item.

UPDATED: Modified design to provide stronger posts, and looser tolerances on the sockets. (2/13/17)

description.text:
This is a custom Raspberry Pi 2/3 Case with an angular aesthetic inspired by many currently popular game consoles. It is the 3rd and most usable revision of the case. The previous 2 designs were not fit for public use due to fragile screw posts and a lack of a Micro SD Card slot. All 3 versions were nearly identical on the exterior, and you may see pictures of all 3 in the listing.

The case is designed with simple cooling, with one strong blower type fan providing intake air and pushing air right over a large heatsink and straight out the back of the case. This cooling design is heavily influenced by laptops and recent game consoles like the Playstation 4. This design has kept my Raspberry Pi 3 running at 1.4ghz while staying at approximately 50 degrees celsius for extended gaming sessions in Retropie. Other stability and temperature testing was done in Raspbian Pixel using benchmark tools like Sysbench and Shell Scripts to provide constant temperature readouts while pushing all CPU cores to 100% usage. If you are lucky enough to own a Pi 3 that can do 1.5ghz, this design could easily keep it cool as the Pi 3's tend to throttle around 82-85c.

Full worklog can be found here:
http://imgur.com/a/vr6Do

Please note:
The mes_30.stl and mes_30_lid_closed.stl files are full models using stand in parts such as the Pi 3, ATXRaspi, and the 5v 50mm blower fan to provide you a general idea on how the device is built. They ARE NOT intended to be printed, only edited. The mes30.stl file has the lid raised above the object to allow you to peer inside using the limited 3D view on Thingiverse. The lid is intended to slide into the case from the back and sit flush with the top as viewable in the mes_30_lid_closed.stl file. These files also have a modified fan duct design for aesthetic reasons. The correct design for the fan duct is included in the other files.

If you are planning on making your own version, please get the 5v, 50mm blower fan first. This is necessary as the mounting hole placement for these blower fans varies greatly. Once you have the fan mounting holes measured, then remix your own version to fit. The fan I used is a Titan 50mm USB powered fan. It is a very powerful and well built fan, however it is quite loud. I wired in circuitry to control its speed and noise. Slowing the fan down by nearly 50% made a dramatic difference in noise while sacrificing less than 5 degrees of cooling power.

  • ATXRaspi Smart Power Controller. Right angle header pins and optional USB port are NOT recommended with the current design. You may need to remix the design yourself if you want to use right angle header pins. Header plugs barely fit inside the case allowing the lid to slide shut. To gain additional clearance, remove the plastic from your header plugs and put heatshrink on them instead.
    https://lowpowerlab.com/guide/atxraspi/

  • Titan 50mm USB/5v Blower Fan
    http://www.performance-pcs.com/50mm-fans/titan-50mm-high-airflow-portable-usb-cooling-fan.html

  • 22mm x 22mm x 25mm Heatsink
    http://www.performance-pcs.com/3m-8810-high-performance-thermally-conductive-adhesive-heatsink-22mm.html

  • 22mm Vandal Resistant Lighted Switch
    http://www.performance-pcs.com/modmytoys-anodized-illuminated-switch-22mm-momentary-power-symbol-matte-black-red.html

  • 0.1" Female Jumper wires
    https://www.adafruit.com/products/1950

  • Panel Mount Ethernet Extension Cable
    https://www.adafruit.com/products/909

    https://www.adafruit.com/products/3258

The screw holes on the object are sized to 2.5mm, and the screws will thread themselves in the plastic. If you go too much larger, you may need to drill out the hole carefully. I got my screws from several old laptops and video cards I had sitting around.

  • Heatshrink of varying sizes and some basic soldering skills.

    http://www.loctiteproducts.com/p/sg_ug_cntrl/overview/Loctite-Super-Glue-ULTRA-Gel-Control.htm

    http://www.performance-pcs.com/video-card-coolers/demciflex-magnetic-fan-dust-filter-custom-graphics-card-filter.html

title: MP Select Mini 1.65mm Z Spacer (No Disassembly Needed!)

description.text:
This is a customized spacer for the Monoprice Select Mini that simply clicks onto the z block. I had to remix the original due to the fact that I am using the 'Monoprice Select Mini spool holder' by Toys (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2006457) which clamps around the outside of the printer preventing me from being able to use the version with the levers as the clamps of the spool holder interfered with them, My solution was to remove the levers and turn one 90 degrees and center it (with some additional support added). I also noted that the Z limit switch is slightly offset from the end of the inside gantry block so I added a small 'paddle' to the bottom arm and a clip to the inside of the top arm to keep the offset correct.

This style of spacer benefits from being able to insert and remove the spacer without disassembling the machine, it has no overhangs and requires no supports at all!

Installation

  1. turn on the printer and move the z-axis up high enough to slip the spacer in without hitting the Z-axis limit switch or any accessories that may be clamped to the outside of the tower.

  2. From the rear of the machine slip the hook side of the spacer with the 'paddle' at the bottom through the gap in the tower and click the spacer in place on the side of the z axis block. Use a thin stick (tongue depressor, small screwdriver, chopstick, etc...) through the front gap to push on the levers to make sure the hooks have clicked in, then pull on the tab to make sure it is secure.

  3. Install your glass bed and re-level as necessary

description.text:
Torches blaze. Campfires cackle. Forest fires roar. Heat and destruction follow the wake of the living flame. Uncontrollable in its baser forms. It is for that very reason mages use fire elementals as a sign of power and control. For something that is so powerful, so useful, so necessary for survival to break free from it's mage is.....more common than you would think. A quick 3D representation of the Raspberry Pi 1B+, Pi 2 and Pi 3 model motherboards using the official specifications. It is not meant to be 3D printed.

Mechanical drawing obtained from here:
http://www.raspiworld.com/images/other/drawings/Raspberry-Pi-1-2-3-Model-B.jpg

The mounting holes, Micro USB power port, HDMI port, 1/8" audio jack, Ethernet Jack, and USB port placement and exterior size is exact to specifications. However, the internal pins and design on these plugs is estimated. I felt these little details were not important when using this model as a stand in for other Raspberry Pi projects.

The size and placement of the Camera port, Display port, SD Card slot, GPIO ports, Broadcom SOC, Ethernet Controller, and DDR Ram chip are all estimated.

Feel free to remix to your heart's content, especially if you have better measurements of the items I estimated or if you have found other mistakes in the model. I've used this model several times without issue, however, I tend to over compensate slightly with sizing of exterior ports.

Please double check all measurements before using this model in your own creation.

description.text:
This is a clean way to add an integrated diversity receiver to your headplay HD! It uses the Realacc rx5808 pro module with OLED, which is fully enclosed and protected with a smoked acrylic display window. It also uses pushbuttons to replace the stock navigation switch, a built in USB serial converter with externally accessible micro USB port for easily updating the module firmware,and two conveniently located forward facing SMA or RP-SMA connectors (your choice). Assembling this unit will require a fair bit of modding to the module, and unfortunately I didn't take many pictures of that process. I'm building another unit for a friend, so I'll document the build better at that point.

You'll need:

  • M2 heat set threaded inserts, 4.8mm length
  • This USB to serial adapter this is optional if you don't need easy firmware update, and I can upload a version without the USB hole.
  • A pair of SMA or RP-SMA extensions with bulkhead nuts, I used these SMA ones
  • 5x m2 screws, 10mm I believe. You can also order them longer and cut to length as necessary
  • 3x 6x6x6mm tactile switch. I got mine from this set
  • Some smoked acrylic or not smoked if tht's your style. 12x12 is way too much and 1/8'' is thicker than I'd like but I made it work.
  • An RX5808 Pro diversity module you dont need the cover obviously, and it doesnt matter if you get the SMA or RP-SMA version if one's out of stock since those will be getting removed anyway.
  • And, finally, a set of the above printed parts, basic hand tools, some random small gauge wire, the receiver cable interconnect from your headplay or a JST SH 6 pin cable, and some soldering finesse.

The basic process is to unscrew the two boards from each other, desolder the built in SMA connectors from the rx5808 pro module, install the acrylic window in the housing, wire the FTDI to the RX5808, replace the threaded module board spacers with the above clearance spacers, and screw the module to the inside of the housing using the m2 inserts. The buttons press in snugly from the back, but will require a bit of a hack to wire up. I will update with details, but it involves scraping off some solder mask and tapping into three traces plus ground. Finally, bolt in the SMA extension bulkheads and solder to the pads on the rear of the module board. then, add the power/audio/video headplay cable, bolt on the cover, plug into the headplay motherboard, and apply the module to the top of the headplay with some strong transfer tape.

I know thats a lot of steps and no pictures, I will update with a more detailed build guide and can answer any questions via messages in the meantime!

comments.text: why is the top and bottom closed
comments.author: dankmemesincorporated

comments.text: This is because of how STL files and slicers work. This object is designed to be printed in vase mode, where the printer makes the continuous outline of the part, so the fact that the stl file appears filled doesn't matter. Actually, if it wasn't filled and if the interior was cut out, the printer nozzle wouldn't follow a coutinous path because it would have to jump back and forth between printing the inside and the outside of each part. Furthermore, slicers have options where you can specify the number if top and bottom layers, i.e. the number of solid layers that you print on th top and the bottom of your parts. To have an open top, just specify "0" as the number of top layers.

description.text:
I recently acquired a Erle Copter drone, and upon assembly I realised that the legs would not touch the ground, and that anyway I would need to do something to allow mounting the camera underneath.
I could have brought the legs on Erle's website, but where is the fun in that?

I designed the legs in 3 parts:
The base plate, which attaches with velcro and is secured with zip ties on my model. I did this so it would be easily removable, and also gave me a platform to fix the gopro to.
The legs, which is pretty self explanatory. I printed them vertically with some support, as it can be seen in the photos. The other parts were simply printed flat on the bed.
And the skids. I tried to make it so they would stay out of the Gopro's field of view. Some tweeking may be needed if you want to use the wide FOV of the camera.

All of the parts can be easily fitted together, I used hot glue to secure them, but it isn't the most aesthetic of doing so, but it certainly works very well.

If you decide to print this, don't forget to mirror the skids, since the file included only does one side.

As a "bonus", I included some photos of my crudely crafted Gopro antivibration mount, which uses ear plugs to cut out the vibration. It works very well!

title: Solid State Relay Hang Bracket - A8 - I3 Clone Printer

description.text:
Bracket is designed to fit above the power supply without screws. It clips on the side and slides down. It uses the shape of the side support to hold it to the printer. The screw heads are counter-sunk. An air channel is designed behind the relay to allow for heat dissipation and it has been tested for 2 hour prints with no issues. If heating develops, the SSR can be flipped, with the internal heat sink (metal part) facing out. In extreme cases, the factory heat sink can also be added.

This mounting location allows the SSRs to be easily fed off the power supply. Both the hot end and bed wires were able to reach the location without issue.
I needed a way to hand the SSR's on my printer. Developed as a block, with the vertical mount cut out.

description.text:
Lorei has 2 sets of fans, one for the extruder and other for the filament, this second fan blows air but it hits the heater block too and not enough air gets to the actual filament.

I found some filament coolers for the Lorei but they replaced the whole fan arm and I wanted to keep the external look as is... so I made this one!

You just print it and use the same screws that currently hold the fan, it gets behind the fan so the external look of your printer stays the same.

UPDATE - 20167-02-14

A new version has been uploaded, it contains small changes like:

  • Bigger air opening
